naling","Paracrine signaling","Endocrine signaling","Synaptic signaling"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis describes \u003Cstrong\u003Eparacrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E, where signaling molecules act on nearby target cells. In \u003Cstrong\u003Eendocrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E hormones travel through the bloodstream to reach distant targets, while paracrine factors only affect local tissue. \u003Cstrong\u003ESynaptic signaling\u003C/strong\u003E involves neurotransmitter release at specialized junctions between neurons. \u003Cstrong\u003EAutocrine signaling\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when cells respond to their own secreted signals. \u003Cstrong\u003EGap junction signaling\u003C/strong\u003E involves direct communication between adjacent cells through protein channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon paracrine signaling molecules include growth factors that regulate cell growth and division, prostaglandins involved in inflammation, and cytokines that mediate immune responses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paracrine signaling occurs between nearby cells through locally diffusing molecules","Growth factors, prostaglandins, and cytokines are common paracrine signaling molecules","Paracrine signals act over short distances unlike endocrine signals which travel through the bloodstream"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96071"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96071"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T23:49:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T23:49:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"dat